    "reasoning": "To implement the module as described, we need to track each bit of the input vector to detect when a bit transitions from 1 to 0. When such a transition occurs, we set the corresponding output bit to 1 and keep it set until a reset occurs. This requires storing the previous value of each bit and comparing it with the current value on each clock cycle. Since this is a synchronous design, all sequential operations occur on the positive edge of the clock. The reset is active high and synchronous, so we initialize all flip-flops to 0 in the reset condition. To ensure correctness, we must carefully handle each bit independently using a loop or individual logic for each bit. We'll create a memory to store the previous input values and use them to compare with the current values.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input clk,\n    input reset,\n    input [31:0] in,\n    output [31:0] out\n);\n\n    // Storage for previous input values\n    logic [31:0] prev_in;\n    \n    // Combinational logic to determine output\n    always @(*) begin\n        out = 0;\n        for (int i = 0; i < 32; i = i + 1) begin\n            if (prev_in[i] == 1 && in[i] == 0)\n                out[i] = 1;\n        end\n    end\n    \n    // Sequential logic to update previous input\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (reset)\n            prev_in <= 0;\n        else\n            prev_in <= in;\n    end\n\nendmodule"
